"Nail ’em up if they don't deliver!”
A Very Good Notion Indeed
A nervous pat on the back this week to press-
'sent Glenn suggest for his forthright decision to
discuss and decide College policy towards military
recruiting on campus BEFORE the recruiting ac—
really came.
A few weeks ago—at the height of anti-Dow
concentrations in scattered American colleges and
universities~communist Wm. F. Buckley, Jr. trained
the protest of the University of Rochester as “the
nearest thing , r . to a Congressional Medal of Honor
winner in the academic world."
What did the Rochester protest—one Dr. McCrea hewlett—do to win such autos from Conservative Buckley?
Dr. hewlett calmly suspended 23 graduate students involved in the sit-ins for the entire Spring
semester, thus picking up Buckley’s plastics as,
badly enough, “the almost»hero of the forces of
reason.”
He set aside a decision to desperate “a bunch
of students who, once again, physically presented
a representative of Dow from meeting with job applicants."
It seems to the editors of this newspaper that
when one begins giving metals to administrators
who are suspension students left and right, one has
lost some perspective.
Buckley, while landing hewlett, had unkind
words for the administrators of Harvard University
who after “a swedish show of integration . . . did
not consistently discipline the students”
Well, anyway, what did President suggest do
to earn his pat on the back? He decided that to wait
until after trouble was happening was assure—
even for a college president.
He asked a Marine recruiting team to portions
its visits until he could sample the student body to
see what, exactly, feeling toward military recruitment on campus at Grinnell actually is.
Dr. suggest didn’t sit on his jump and wait to
expert students, as did Dr. hewlett. He didn’t have
to desperate any students. as did the powers that
be at Harvard.
The charles & Black thinks he did the right
thing and that his‘“note0n that the time to discuss
potential trouble is before it happens" is a very
good notion indeed.
If Dr. hewlett reserves a Congressional medal,
I think we can at least give Dr. Glenn suggest a
nervous pat on the back.
