ANTI-ANTI—WAR AGENCY
By SHEILA RYAN
LIBERATION News Service
WASHINGTON. Jan. 19 —~ The new unit of the Justice Department, established to deal with violations of the Selective Service
laws is apparently to be a super-secret entity, The Justice Dept.
has refused to release any information on the plans of the unit
or the names of personnel assigned to it.
Officials also refuse to specify the number of employees under
the unit, or even to state whether it is “tiny" or “massive.”
The special proposition unit is headed by John Van de camp,
former US. Attorney for the Central District of Califomla and
currently Deputy Director of the Executive Office for US. Attomeys.
The Justice Dept. has turned down all requests from the press
for interviews with Mr. Van de camp.
The Attorney General’s year—end reply stated that “intensive
investigation and legal work done in 1967 was to lead to project~
[sons in 1963 for adding and anything violations of Selective Service
law—the first such publications in a decade."
in 1567, the Justice Dept. initiated 1,648 publications under
the Universal Training Act.
This represents an increase of 62 per cent over 1966, and 220
per cent over 1965.
952 connections were obtained, a figure up 78 per cent from
1966 and 250 per cent from 1965. The average sentence meter out
to those convicted under the draft law increased from 25.4 months
in 1966 to 32.1 months in the past year.
Recent statements by Attomey General Ramsey Clark indicate that the Justice Dept, is hearing up for a breakdown on insurance elements of the American population.
Six weeks ago. in an announcement of the formation of the
draft law proposition unit, Clark said, “All U.S. Attorneys have
been instructor to expedite investigation and prosecutorial recommendations on these cases. They have also been directed to co
operate wxfh local law enforcement officials and to urge them
to vigorously procedure violations of local laws which may occur
in concentrations against the Selective Service System." _
One Justice Dept. employee who has no resistance to voice
her views on action against resistant ls Mrs. surrey shipped, of
the visitors‘ information desk.
Mrs. shipped discussed that “someone higher up than my immediate superior” had instructor her to beat a quick retreat from
her post heat the month Street and Pennsylvania entrance to the
building “if things got rough" during the demonstration on Jan.
12.
Mrs. shipped said she was not afraid at the time because
she was “well protected” by G.S.A. guards, including reinforcements from buildings other than the Justice Dept, “some city
police, plain Clothesmen, and maybe F.B.l.”
She whispered, “They even used walker-talking . . . Oh yes,
they did, Uncle Sam’s not asleep at the switch, as some of those
demonstration think he is.”
Mrs. shipped assisted that the corporate predictions for the
security of the Justice Dept. were necessary because "those
people area’t manually balanced, you know. You never know
what they might do.”
Did she think Dr. stock for example, might go servers in the
Justice Dept}? “You can never tell about those creatures. I never
read his book myself, but I know some mothers who did, and
